::: {#data-preparation .section .level1}
*Data Preparation*
==================

::: {#data-in-long-format .section .level2}
*Data in long format*
---------------------

We convert the data to the long format:

``` {.r}
CMD.Long <- dplyr::select(main,set,group,id,age,sex,education, I_1:Z_16) %>%
  gather(I_1:Z_16, key = "Item", value = "Rating", na.rm = TRUE) %>% 
  separate(col = Item, into = c("Condition",'Item'), sep = "_") %>% 
  arrange(set)
cmdc=CMD.Long #longformat
```

Here are the main factors of our study:

-   **Sets** (For different randomization:1 to 10)\
-   **Groups** (from 1 to 17)\
-   **IDs** (Unique for each participants)\
-   **Conditions** (*First*, *Collective*, *Second*)and\
-   **Items** (1 to 16).

Here we set all to factors and re-order their levels for illustration
purposes:

``` {.r}
cmdc$group=as.factor(cmdc$group)
cmdc$set=as.factor(cmdc$set)
cmdc$id=as.factor(cmdc$id)
cmdc$sex=as.factor(cmdc$sex)
cmdc$Condition=as.factor(cmdc$Condition)
cmdc$Item=as.factor(cmdc$Item)
cmdc$Condition=dplyr::recode(
cmdc$Condition, 'C'='Collective', 'I'='First', 'Z' = 'Second' )
#re_name
```
:::

::: {#randomization .section .level2}
Randomization
-------------

For each group the *discussed* items were pseudo-randomized according to
their sets, see below:

-   Group1: **Action**: 1,2,3,4 - **Inaction**: 9,10,11,12

-   Group2: **Action**: 2,3,4,5 - **Inaction**: 10,11,12,13

-   Group3: **Action**: 3,4,5,6 - **Inaction**: 11,12,13,14

-   Group4: **Action**: 4,5,6,7 - **Inaction**: 12,13,14,15

-   Group5: **Action**: 5,6,7,8 - **Inaction**: 13,14,15,16

-   Group6: **Action**: 6,7,8,1 - **Inaction**: 14,15,16,9

-   Group7: **Action**: 7,8,1,2 - **Inaction**: 15,16,9,10

-   Group8: **Action**: 8,1,2,3 - **Inaction**: 16,9,10,11

-   Group9: **Action**: 1,3,5,7 - **Inaction**: 9,11,13,15

-   Group10:**Action**: 2,4,6,8 - **Inaction**: 10,12,14,16

-   Group11 to Group 17 are the same as 1 to 7

Here are

           Action    Inaction
  -------- --------- -------------
  Group1   1,2,3,4   9,10,11,12
  Group2   2,3,4,5   10,11,12,13
  Group3   3,4,5,6   11,12,13,14
  Group4   4,5,6,7   12,13,14,15
  Group5   5,6,7,8   13.14,15,16
  Group6   6,7,8,1   14,15,16,9
  Group7   7,8,1,2   15,16,9,10
  Group8   8,1,2,3   16,9,10,11
  Group9   1,3,5,7   2,4,6,8

  :  Randomization of discussed items acrossed groups

Here we define *discussed* items for each group according to their *Set*
(see above). We also define a new factor:**Mode**\
**Mode** includes three levels: *discussed* or *undiscussed* for items
in **J1** (First *Pre-Discussion* Judgments) or **J2**(Second
*Post-Discussion* Judgments)

Below is the code for randomization in group 1, for the rest of the
groups see the .RMD file

``` {.r}
#group1: Collective: 1,2,3,4,9,10,11,12
Group1= filter(cmdc, set=='1')
Group1$Mode= dplyr::if_else(Group1$Item =='1' |
                            Group1$Item =='2' |
                            Group1$Item =='3' |
                            Group1$Item =='4' |
                            Group1$Item =='9' |
                            Group1$Item =='10'|
                            Group1$Item =='11'|
                            Group1$Item=='12','Discussed','Undiscussed')
Group1.c=filter(Group1, Condition=='Collective')
Group1.c$Item=dplyr::recode(Group1.c$Item, 
                            '1'= '1', '2'= '2', '3'='3',
                            '4' = '4', '5'= '9', '6' = '10', 
                            '7' = '11', '8' = '12')
```

Here we bind all of the groups:

``` {.r}
#Now we bind all the above groups:

G=rbind(Group1,Group2,Group3,Group4,Group5,Group6,Group7,Group8,Group9,Group10)
G.c =rbind(Group1.c,Group2.c,Group3.c,Group4.c,Group5.c,Group6.c,Group7.c,Group8.c,Group9.c,Group10.c)


#non-collective (I1 and I2)
data=filter(G,Condition != 'Collective')
data=rbind(data,G.c)
data$Condition=as.factor(data$Condition)

#collective

data.c=filter(data, data$Condition == 'Collective')
data.c$Mode= 'Collective'
data.I=filter(data, data$Condition!= 'Collective')

Data=rbind(data.c,data.I)

Data$Mode= dplyr::if_else(Data$Condition =='Collective' ,'Collective',Data$Mode)
```

This is to define the factor **type** with two levels:

-   *Action* (8 items)\
-   *In\_Action* (8 items)

``` {.r}
#Action vs In_action  
Data$type= dplyr::if_else( Data$Item =='1' 
                          |Data$Item =='2' 
                          |Data$Item =='3' 
                          |Data$Item =='4' 
                          |Data$Item =='5' 
                          |Data$Item =='6' 
                          |Data$Item =='7' 
                          |Data$Item =='8' ,'Action','InAction')
```
:::

::: {#outlier-dectection .section .level2}
*Outlier Dectection*
--------------------

In this section we detect the outliers at group level with different
methods. For this, we will need use a function called
**check\_outliers** which is documented in RDocumentation
[**here**](https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/performance/versions/0.5.0/topics/check_outliers)

::: {#outlier-detection-setup .section .level3}
### *Outlier Detection Setup*

We first need to prepare the data in the right format which gives each
group's

-   **a.** *ratings before the discussion (J1)*\
-   **b.** *collective ratings (JC)*\
-   **c.** *ratings after the discussion (J2)*

First we divide the dataset into three parts: *First*, *Second* and
*Collective* and then each of them to *Discussed* vs.Â *Undiscuessed*
subdivision:

``` {.r}
datac=Data
#division by condition
first=filter(datac,Condition=='First')
second=filter(datac,Condition=='Second')
collective=filter(datac,Condition=='Collective')

#division by Mode:discussed and undiscussed 
#in J1 (i.e. pre-discussion)
fd=dplyr::filter(first,Mode=='Discussed') %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id,Item,group) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(J1D = mean(Rating)) 

fu=dplyr::filter(first,Mode=='Undiscussed') %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id,Item,group) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(J1U = mean(Rating)) 
          
#division by Mode:discussed and undiscussed 
#in J2 (i.e. postdiscussion)
sd=dplyr::filter(second,Mode=='Discussed') %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id,Item,group) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(J2D = mean(Rating))

su=dplyr::filter(second,Mode=='Undiscussed') %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id,Item,group) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(J2U = mean(Rating))

##division by Mode:collective (i.e. post-discussion)
c=collective %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id,Item,group) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(JC = mean(Rating))

GDT=merge(fd,c,by=c('id','group','Item'))
IGD=merge(GDT,sd,by=c('id','group','Item')) ##discussed items-including Collective
IGU=merge(fu,su,by=c('id','group','Item'))  ##undiscussed items
```

Now we average all responses at group level:

``` {.r}
TD=dplyr::filter(IGD,) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(group) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(J1D = mean(J1D),JC=mean(JC),J2D=mean(J2D))

TU=dplyr::filter(IGU,) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(group) %>%
 dplyr:: summarise(J1U = mean(J1U),J2U=mean(J2U))

DT=merge(TD,TU,by=c('group'))
DT=arrange(DT,by=group)
```

Here we plot a box-plot to visualize the outliers in **JC** (Collective
Judgments) at group level

``` {.r}
##Outliers
g1=ggplot (DT, aes (y = JC))  + geom_boxplot () +
  labs(title = "Collective responses with outlier",y = "Collective Ratings")

g1 +theme_minimal()+ coord_flip()
```

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}

According to the boxplot above,the collective response with the lowest
rating seems to be an outlier.

To perform tests for outlier detection, we use **outlier\_function**
which uses a composite measure combined of different methods including:

-   *Cook's Distance*,
-   *Pareto*,
-   *Z-scores*,
-   *IQR*,
-   *Mahalanobis Distance*,
-   *Robust Mahalanobis Distance*,
-   *Minimum Covariance Determinant (MCD)*,
-   *Invariant Coordinate Selection (ICS)*,
-   *OPTICS*,
-   *Isolation Forest*,
-   *Local Outlier Factor*.

We use this composite measurement in a **Multivariate approach** which
includes ratings for **Collective** as well ass **Discussed**,
**Undiscussed** items for **First** and **Second** condition, but at
group level.

For documentation and references please check here
[**outlier\_function**](https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/performance/versions/0.5.0/topics/check_outliers)

``` {.r}
Outliers=performance::check_outliers(DT[,c(2,3,4,5,6)], method="all")#multivariate  
Outliers.2=performance::check_outliers(DT[c(4)],c("zscore", "mahalanobis", "igr")) #univariate 
```

Here is the output of the outlier check shows an outlier:

``` {.r}
plot(Outliers)
```

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}

``` {.r}
print(Outliers)
```

    ## Warning: 1 outliers detected (cases 4).

``` {.r}
plot(Outliers.2)
```

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}

``` {.r}
print(Outliers.2)
```

    ## Warning: 1 outliers detected (cases 4).

The composite methods of multivariate approach as well as univariate
approach, similarly tells us group 4 is an outlier. Now we check the
data without the outlier group to make sure the other groups are fine:

In addition to the composite method above, we use **outliers** library
for three univariate methods, *grubbs*, *dixon* and *chisq* proposed for
small sample sizes (see the library documentation for the references)

``` {.r}
test1 = outliers::grubbs.test(DT$JC)
print(test1)
```

    ## 
    ##  Grubbs test for one outlier
    ## 
    ## data:  DT$JC
    ## G = 3.43389, U = 0.21697, p-value = 2.02e-05
    ## alternative hypothesis: lowest value 1.5 is an outlier

``` {.r}
test2 = outliers::dixon.test(DT$JC)
print(test2)
```

    ## 
    ##  Dixon test for outliers
    ## 
    ## data:  DT$JC
    ## Q = 0.75, p-value < 2.2e-16
    ## alternative hypothesis: lowest value 1.5 is an outlier

``` {.r}
test3 = outliers::chisq.out.test(DT$JC, variance=var(DT$JC))
print(test3)
```

    ## 
    ##  chi-squared test for outlier
    ## 
    ## data:  DT$JC
    ## X-squared = 11.792, p-value = 0.000595
    ## alternative hypothesis: lowest value 1.5 is an outlier

Different methods detect group 4 (Mean JC=1.5) as an outlier, therefore,
we exclude group 4 from the data for the rest of the analysis.

::: {#mixed-effect-models .section .level1}
**Mixed Effect Models**
=======================

Since the dependent variable (i.e.Â moral judgment) is measured in Likert
scale, we used ordinal regression models. For that, we first need to
convert our variables to *Factors*. See the documentation for
**ordinal** package for more information.

``` {.r}
D=df.main
D$Rating=as.factor(D$Rating)
D$Item=as.factor(D$Item)
D$group=as.factor(D$group)
D$id=as.factor(D$id)
```

We first check how adding different random slopes (random factors) would
improve our model:

``` {.r}
model1=ordinal::clmm(Rating ~ Condition  + (1|Item)  , data=D) #Random:item

model2=ordinal::clmm(Rating ~ Condition  + (1|group/id) , data=D) #Random:group and id

model3=ordinal::clmm(Rating ~ Condition  + (1|Item) + (1|group/id) , data=D)#Random:group, id and item 
```

Table of the winning model follows:

We compare different models above with **anova** function

  -------------------------------------------------------------------
       Â         no.par    AIC    logLik   LR.stat   df   Pr(\>Chisq)
  ------------ -------- ------- -------- --------- ---- -------------
   **model1**     9      9801    -4891      NA      NA       NA

   **model2**     10     10352   -5166     -549     1         1

   **model3**     11     9616    -4797     737.8    1    1.831e-162
  -------------------------------------------------------------------

According to **anova** output (see above) the model with **Item** as
random factors and **id** per **group** as nested factors is the best
fit

Here we report the summary of the winning model (i.e.Â model 3)

``` {.r}
sum3=summary(model3)
stargazer(sum3$coefficients, type = "LaTeX")
```

According to the winning model, the ratings of **Condition:**
*Collective* is significantly different from *First* and *Second*
condition. We will later use Bayesian Regressions to make sure if the
**First** and **Second** posterior distribution are different.

We use **emmeans function** for pairwise comparison between the
condition

``` {.r}
comp=emmeans(model3, specs = pairwise ~ Condition)
compcont=comp$contrasts
```

Finally, to compare the utilitarian score of discussed and undiscussed
items before and after the discussion, we excluded collective judgments
and only include First and Second conditions in a new model. In this
model, we compared change of utilitarian score as a function of
interaction between Condition (First vs.Â Second) and Mode (discussed
vs.Â undiscussed).

Here we use this model to check the effect of the discussion in
*Discussed* vs.Â *Undiscussed* items in **Condition:** *First* and
*Second*. First we exclude the **Collective** condition from the dataset
and later we use **Mode** with two levels of *Discussed*
vs.Â *Undiscussed* items as a new factor in out model.

``` {.r}
D3=filter(D,Condition!='Collective')
model.int=ordinal::clmm(Rating ~ Condition * Mode + (1|Item) + (1|group/id) , data=D3)
```

``` {.r}
sum.int=summary(model.int)
stargazer(sum.int$coefficients, type = "LaTeX")
```

``` {.r}
comp3=emmeans(model.int, specs = pairwise ~ Condition * Mode)
compcont3=comp3$contrasts
```

::: {#linear-mixed-effect-model .section .level2}
Linear Mixed Effect Model
-------------------------

Alternatively, we run a similar model by using linear mixed effect
models.In order to make sure that the assumption of normal distribution
did not affect our result in our logistic model described, we adopt this
alternative analysis. Here, instead of considering items as random
slopes, we averaged them across individuals in different condition.

``` {.r}
avg=filter(Data,group!=4) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(group,id,Condition) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(J = mean(Rating))
```

    ## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'group', 'id' (override with `.groups` argument)

``` {.r}
m1=lme4::lmer(J ~ Condition  + (1|group/id) , data = avg)
```

``` {.r}
summary(m1)
```

\#Baysian Mixed Models

In the main text we report an analysis with a weakly informative prior
(model betas drawn from `normal(0,1)`).

``` {.r}
Prior <-set_prior("normal(0,1)", class="b")

formula = Rating ~ Condition +  (1|group/id) + (1|Item) 
fit_b <- brm(formula,
  data = Data,
  prior= Prior,
  cores = 2,
  chains = 5,
  iter = 4000,
  file="fit_ful.rda"
)
```

``` {.r}
sum_fit=summary(fit_b)
stargazer(sum_fit$fixed, type = "LaTeX")
stargazer(sum_fit$random, type = "LaTeX")
```

``` {.r}
h1 = hypothesis(fit_b,"ConditionCollective =0")
h2 = hypothesis(fit_b, hypothesis = 'ConditionSecond = 0')
plot(h1)
```
